04462nam a22005055i 9780226825700DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226825700  a(DE-B1597)653607  a(OCoLC)1394871648  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aRA643.86.M32bB35 2024 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a362.196979200968972231 aTrinitapoli, Jenny, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut13aAn Epidemic of Uncertainty :bNavigating HIV and Young Adulthood in Malawi /cJenny Trinitapoli. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b24 halftones, 22 line drawings, 6 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Ten Years in Balaka -- t3. Uncertainty Demography -- t4. The Scope of HIV Uncertainty -- t5. HIV Uncertainty and the Limits of Testing -- t6. Relationship Uncertainty and Marriage Instability -- t7. Call the Ankhoswe -- t8. Ultimate Uncertainties and the Mortality Landscape -- t9. Conclusion. Varieties of Uncertainty in Balaka -- tAcknowledgments -- tAppendix. Mortality Trends in Malawi, 1999–2020 -- tGlossary of Chichewa and Technical Terms -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA decade-long study of young adulthood in Malawi that demonstrates the impact of widespread HIV status uncertainty, laying bare the sociological implications of what is not known. An Epidemic of Uncertainty advances a new framework for studying social life by emphasizing something social scientists routinely omit from their theories, models, and measures–what people know they don’t know. Taking Malawi’s ongoing AIDS epidemic as an entry point, Jenny Trinitapoli shows that despite admirable declines in new HIV infections and AIDS-related mortality, an epidemic of uncertainty persists; at any given point in time, fully half of Malawian young adults don’t know their HIV status. Reckoning with the impact of this uncertainty within the bustling trading town of Balaka, Trinitapoli argues that HIV-related uncertainty is measurable, pervasive, and impervious to biomedical solutions, with consequences that expand into multiple domains of life, including relationship stability, fertility, and health. Over the duration of a groundbreaking decade-long longitudinal study, rich survey data and poignant ethnographic vignettes vividly depict how individual lives and population patterns unfold against the backdrop of an ever-evolving epidemic. Even as HIV is transformed from a progressive, fatal disease to a chronic and manageable condition, the accompanying epidemic of uncertainty remains fundamental to understanding social life in this part of the world. Insisting that known unknowns can and should be integrated into social-scientific models of human behavior, An Epidemic of Uncertainty treats uncertainty as an enduring aspect, a central feature, and a powerful force in everyday life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAIDS (Disease)xSocial aspectszMalawizBalaka. 0aPopulationxHealth aspects. 0aRiskxSociological aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  auncertainty, Malawi, HIV/AIDS, global health, fertility, population studies, longitudinal survey, family formation, mortality, ethnographic.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079732940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226825700423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226825700/original  a978-3-11-079732-9  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles